00:08:48.510 --> 00:08:52.170
So without further ado, let's
take a little history lesson

00:08:52.170 --> 00:08:55.830
and look at where Pay With
Square originated.

00:08:55.830 --> 00:08:58.170
This was our Card Case
application.

00:08:58.170 --> 00:09:00.250
This is what our app used
to look like on Android.

00:09:00.250 --> 00:09:03.460
This was well before Android
design guidelines were out.

00:09:03.460 --> 00:09:07.110
This is what we call a
skeuomorphic design.

00:09:07.110 --> 00:09:09.650
So skeuomorphic means you're
trying to make an application

00:09:09.650 --> 00:09:11.900
look like a real world object.

00:09:11.900 --> 00:09:14.920
Now in this case, obviously,
it looks like this gorgeous

00:09:14.920 --> 00:09:16.240
leather wallet.

00:09:16.240 --> 00:09:18.240
And it has cards in there.

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:21.490
And it looks like
something real.

00:09:21.490 --> 00:09:23.630
It's pretty.

00:09:23.630 --> 00:09:26.050
People really loved the look.

00:09:26.050 --> 00:09:28.410
But from a design perspective,
it has a lot

00:09:28.410 --> 00:09:31.050
of interaction problems.

00:09:31.050 --> 00:09:34.810
So first of all, let's look
at technically on Android.

00:09:34.810 --> 00:09:36.870
This is really hard
to pull off.

00:09:36.870 --> 00:09:40.190
I worked a lot of hours trying
to get this thing to look

00:09:40.190 --> 00:09:41.500
right on Android.

00:09:41.500 --> 00:09:44.340
And I think, technically,
it just slowed us down.

00:09:44.340 --> 00:09:48.010
Also, as more and more screen
sizes come out, stretching a

00:09:48.010 --> 00:09:51.900
bitmap like this ends up
producing fuzzy graphics, and

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:53.950
that's not cool.

00:09:53.950 --> 00:09:57.400
From a usability perspective,
you can only hold, really,

00:09:57.400 --> 00:09:59.000
four cards.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:01.480
The top card, that's your
merchant card, that actually

00:10:01.480 --> 00:10:03.410
has a hologram in the corner.

00:10:03.410 --> 00:10:06.340
And I think Apple copied us.

00:10:06.340 --> 00:10:08.210
When they move their phone, they
have a little hologram on

00:10:08.210 --> 00:10:10.270
their little, shiny,
silver thing.

00:10:10.270 --> 00:10:13.190
We did that in our app also.

00:10:13.190 --> 00:10:15.900
But for the merchants, you
can only hold four cards.

00:10:15.900 --> 00:10:18.790
So that's a problem
scalability-wise.

00:10:18.790 --> 00:10:20.960
Also, to actually make a payment
with this product, you

00:10:20.960 --> 00:10:23.600
had to first drag a card
out of the pocket and

00:10:23.600 --> 00:10:24.600
then press a button.

00:10:24.600 --> 00:10:26.610
So it's multiple taps
just to perform

00:10:26.610 --> 00:10:28.470
the most basic operation.

00:10:28.470 --> 00:10:30.930
To see nearby merchants,
you had to tap the

00:10:30.930 --> 00:10:32.280
Explore Places button.

00:10:32.280 --> 00:10:37.630
Again, it's multiple taps to
get to anywhere in the app.

00:10:37.630 --> 00:10:39.650
Well, the good thing
is, it's pretty.

00:10:39.650 --> 00:10:42.720
The problems are, it requires
multiple taps to do anything.

00:10:42.720 --> 00:10:44.290
It's technically very
challenging.

00:10:44.290 --> 00:10:45.720
It slows us down.

00:10:45.720 --> 00:10:48.670
And as phones get bigger,
it looks more fuzzy.

00:10:48.670 --> 00:10:51.170
So we threw it all away.

00:10:51.170 --> 00:10:52.810
We completely redid it.

00:10:52.810 --> 00:10:54.780
And this is what Pay With
Square looks like today.

00:10:54.780 --> 00:10:57.740
These are actually some of
the secondary screens.

00:10:57.740 --> 00:11:00.440
So on the left, you see
the Twitter view.

00:11:00.440 --> 00:11:02.530
And as you can see, it
has an action bar.

00:11:02.530 --> 00:11:03.360
It has a view pager.

00:11:03.360 --> 00:11:06.190
You can do the whole horizontal
swipe gesture.

00:11:06.190 --> 00:11:08.230
On the right, I'll get
more into the detail

00:11:08.230 --> 00:11:09.480
on that in a minute.

00:11:11.980 --> 00:11:13.990
It's definitely an
Android app now.

00:11:13.990 --> 00:11:16.240
No one is going to look at
this and say that's a

00:11:16.240 --> 00:11:18.220
skeuomorphic design or
that's an iPhone app.

00:11:18.220 --> 00:11:21.080
It looks totally like Android.

00:11:21.080 --> 00:11:23.950
What I'm not showing here is,
when we first started

00:11:23.950 --> 00:11:27.700
prototyping this, we went
with a dark theme.

00:11:27.700 --> 00:11:30.190
So it was a lot of
black on black.

00:11:30.190 --> 00:11:32.330
And it looked kind of dreary.

00:11:32.330 --> 00:11:35.790
It looked, maybe, the app feel
like you're in a nightclub.

00:11:35.790 --> 00:11:38.160
So we ended up going
with a light theme.

00:11:38.160 --> 00:11:40.740
And I think it's totally
appropriate for a dark theme

00:11:40.740 --> 00:11:42.260
in a music player app,
which you're

00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:43.820
going to see in a minute.

00:11:43.820 --> 00:11:46.370
But for a payments application,
the light theme

00:11:46.370 --> 00:11:47.030
worked better.

00:11:47.030 --> 00:11:49.160
We're also using dark
action bars.

00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:51.810
In the original iteration of
this, the action bar color

00:11:51.810 --> 00:11:53.390
would change, depending
on what merchant you

00:11:53.390 --> 00:11:54.520
were looking at.

00:11:54.520 --> 00:11:57.780
Each merchant had a theme and
a graphic, so it became more

00:11:57.780 --> 00:11:59.850
of a showcase for
the merchants.

00:11:59.850 --> 00:12:01.940
But I think we came to the
conclusion that it looked a

00:12:01.940 --> 00:12:05.110
little gaudy to be changing
the color constantly.

00:12:05.110 --> 00:12:07.590
And again, that was really nasty
to implement, because

00:12:07.590 --> 00:12:09.680
you can't change the theme of
an activity after you've

00:12:09.680 --> 00:12:13.520
launched it, without
some heroic hacks.

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:16.120
So we went back to a more
streamlined, basic approach

00:12:16.120 --> 00:12:18.180
with the light theme and
the dark action bar.

00:12:18.180 --> 00:12:19.615
So I really like where
it landed.

00:12:23.690 --> 00:12:26.620
Let's walk through the product
and see what it actually does.

00:12:26.620 --> 00:12:28.730
So obviously, we all
want bacon, right?

00:12:28.730 --> 00:12:29.710
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:12:29.710 --> 00:12:30.050
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:30.050 --> 00:12:31.020
ERIC BURKE: Yeah.

00:12:31.020 --> 00:12:33.280
A round of applause for bacon.

00:12:33.280 --> 00:12:35.700
So this is all about
making payments.

00:12:35.700 --> 00:12:37.750
So when you pull out the app
and launch it, this is your

00:12:37.750 --> 00:12:38.930
home screen.

00:12:38.930 --> 00:12:40.630
This is the Directory view.

00:12:40.630 --> 00:12:42.440
At the top, you see,
what we call, the

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:43.600
Curated Merchants view.

00:12:43.600 --> 00:12:45.590
These are some of our
featured merchants.

00:12:45.590 --> 00:12:48.970
It's a gallery that slides
from left to right.

00:12:48.970 --> 00:12:51.750
It's full-bleed image.

00:12:51.750 --> 00:12:53.040
It has the little overlay
in the middle.

00:12:53.040 --> 00:12:56.430
But it just is a gorgeous
representation of the best

00:12:56.430 --> 00:12:57.370
merchants in the system.

00:12:57.370 --> 00:13:00.020
Below that, we have
a list view that

00:13:00.020 --> 00:13:01.760
shows nearby merchants.

00:13:01.760 --> 00:13:04.920
And you can fit a lot more
information into this design.

00:13:04.920 --> 00:13:07.450
You can fit in information
about specials.

00:13:07.450 --> 00:13:10.740
You can fit in functionality
to open a tab.

00:13:10.740 --> 00:13:12.870
You can fit in the distance.

00:13:12.870 --> 00:13:16.090
So contrast this with the
original Card Case design

00:13:16.090 --> 00:13:19.860
where it was this gorgeous piece
of leather with cards.

00:13:19.860 --> 00:13:21.890
But none of that was
ever actionable.

00:13:21.890 --> 00:13:24.700
You had to go through multiple
taps to actually do anything.

00:13:24.700 --> 00:13:28.350
So a key part of this design is
to reduce friction and make

00:13:28.350 --> 00:13:30.570
the payment experience
effortless.

00:13:30.570 --> 00:13:33.910
So by reducing the number of
taps, fitting more information

00:13:33.910 --> 00:13:36.080
into the main screen, the whole
user interface becomes a

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:37.670
lot more usable.

00:13:37.670 --> 00:13:39.610
So when you want your
bacon, you tap the

00:13:39.610 --> 00:13:41.700
button to open a tab.

00:13:41.700 --> 00:13:43.590
And then you walk up to
the Bacon Bacon truck.

00:13:43.590 --> 00:13:45.020
You place your order.

00:13:45.020 --> 00:13:47.250
And then you say,
put it on Eric.

00:13:47.250 --> 00:13:51.090
And they will see my photo
on their register,

00:13:51.090 --> 00:13:52.580
along with my name.

00:13:52.580 --> 00:13:54.110
And they can tap a button
to charge me.

00:13:54.110 --> 00:13:55.860
And then I can put my phone
away, and I'm done.

00:13:55.860 --> 00:13:57.570
And I have my delicious bacon.

00:13:57.570 --> 00:13:59.550
And I've made a payment.

00:13:59.550 --> 00:14:02.730
So internally at Square, we talk
a lot about the notion of

00:14:02.730 --> 00:14:04.120
humanizing payments.

00:14:04.120 --> 00:14:06.580
We'd rather the payment
experience be about an

00:14:06.580 --> 00:14:09.690
exchange between two people,
rather than an exchange

00:14:09.690 --> 00:14:11.100
between you and the
technology.

00:14:11.100 --> 00:14:14.020
So we really want to reduce the
number of taps and make

00:14:14.020 --> 00:14:17.160
the app as effortless
as possible.

00:14:17.160 --> 00:14:19.260
So we can take this
one step farther.

00:14:19.260 --> 00:14:22.120
We can actually enable a feature
called Auto Tab.

00:14:22.120 --> 00:14:25.230
So this app is deceptively--

00:14:25.230 --> 00:14:26.960
it looks like a really
simple app.

00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:29.080
There are only a few screens in
the app, but it's actually,

00:14:29.080 --> 00:14:32.510
technically, really difficult
to code something like this.

00:14:32.510 --> 00:14:35.420
So with Auto Tabs, you can
put your phone away.

00:14:35.420 --> 00:14:37.300
And then, as you're walking
around, when you get within a

00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:39.810
certain radius of your favorite
merchant, it'll

00:14:39.810 --> 00:14:41.330
automatically open a tab.

00:14:41.330 --> 00:14:46.800
So if I like coffee, I can set
up an auto tab for Sightglass

00:14:46.800 --> 00:14:48.780
Coffee, which is just a few
blocks away from here.

00:14:48.780 --> 00:14:50.620
I highly recommend it.

00:14:50.620 --> 00:14:53.620
Also San Francisco Baking
Company is another great

00:14:53.620 --> 00:14:55.050
merchant that's a
few blocks away.

00:14:55.050 --> 00:14:58.000
So I think these small
businesses would be thrilled

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:02.330
if 700 or 800 people installed
the app and just did a cash

00:15:02.330 --> 00:15:04.930
mob and walked in and ordered
these amazing cookies or this

00:15:04.930 --> 00:15:06.840
amazing coffee.

00:15:06.840 --> 00:15:08.120
So that's my product plug.

00:15:08.120 --> 00:15:10.330
But with Auto Tabs,
it's the ultimate.

00:15:10.330 --> 00:15:12.470
You never have to touch
your phone.

00:15:12.470 --> 00:15:15.010
So the technology
just disappears.

00:15:15.010 --> 00:15:18.430
So we put a lot of emphasis on
pixel pushing, and making

00:15:18.430 --> 00:15:19.950
everything the right
colors, and getting

00:15:19.950 --> 00:15:21.430
the alignment perfect.

00:15:21.430 --> 00:15:23.990
But in reality, our goal is to
make the interface vanish

00:15:23.990 --> 00:15:25.000
completely.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:27.100
And that's the goal of Pay With
Square, is just to make

00:15:27.100 --> 00:15:29.900
it go away.

00:15:29.900 --> 00:15:32.470
So we did bring cards
back in the latest

00:15:32.470 --> 00:15:33.700
iteration of the app.

00:15:33.700 --> 00:15:35.690
So the first screen shot,
I showed you a

00:15:35.690 --> 00:15:37.240
skeuomorphic design.

00:15:37.240 --> 00:15:38.760
We got rid of the cards.

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:41.290
And what we found was that the
user interface was a little

00:15:41.290 --> 00:15:41.850
bit boring.

00:15:41.850 --> 00:15:44.330
And it was just a bunch of
images with list views.

00:15:44.330 --> 00:15:46.260
So we brought back, in
the latest iteration,

00:15:46.260 --> 00:15:47.690
the notion of cards.

00:15:47.690 --> 00:15:49.840
And I really love the
way these look.

00:15:49.840 --> 00:15:51.730
They're not shaped like
a credit card.

00:15:51.730 --> 00:15:54.590
They're actually shaped like a
square with rounded corners.

00:15:54.590 --> 00:15:56.740
We do that a lot in our web
site and our applications,

00:15:56.740 --> 00:15:58.750
because our company's called
Square and that's what our

00:15:58.750 --> 00:15:59.570
logo looks like.

00:15:59.570 --> 00:16:03.240
And I made a little square
robot here for my shirt.

00:16:03.240 --> 00:16:07.670
So cards are great because it's
something tangible that

00:16:07.670 --> 00:16:09.410
humans can relate to.

00:16:09.410 --> 00:16:11.080
It's something that
you can touch.

00:16:11.080 --> 00:16:12.420
You can share cards.

00:16:12.420 --> 00:16:16.820
You'll see the same card on the
web site, in your Android

00:16:16.820 --> 00:16:18.760
phone, on the iPhone.

00:16:18.760 --> 00:16:20.680
You can email cards.

00:16:20.680 --> 00:16:23.240
This is a showcase for the
merchants, so the merchant's

00:16:23.240 --> 00:16:24.840
photos show up on here.

00:16:24.840 --> 00:16:27.250
The merchants can put
menus on here.

00:16:27.250 --> 00:16:29.160
Eventually, we're going to
have more information,

00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:30.330
directions to the merchant.

00:16:30.330 --> 00:16:33.670
You can have punch cards,
specials, discounts,

00:16:33.670 --> 00:16:34.740
first-visit rewards.

00:16:34.740 --> 00:16:37.280
All that stuff shows
up on the card.

00:16:37.280 --> 00:16:41.920
So a card is a concrete,
tangible thing in your UI that

00:16:41.920 --> 00:16:44.390
users can explore and
play around with.

00:16:44.390 --> 00:16:47.770
And it's a delightful way to
do the user interface.

00:16:47.770 --> 00:16:50.320
But even with the cards,
it's not designed to be

00:16:50.320 --> 00:16:51.050
skeuomorphic.

00:16:51.050 --> 00:16:54.490
It's not designed to stray
too far from an

00:16:54.490 --> 00:16:56.080
Android-inspired feel.

00:16:56.080 --> 00:17:00.200
So I really like what
we did here.

00:17:00.200 --> 00:17:03.700
For images, getting a
little geeky here.

00:17:03.700 --> 00:17:05.599
The server provides
the images to us.

00:17:05.599 --> 00:17:07.220
Since there's so many different
screen sizes, we

00:17:07.220 --> 00:17:09.280
actually have a library.

00:17:09.280 --> 00:17:10.109
It's internal.

00:17:10.109 --> 00:17:11.599
I can't really share it
with you right now.

00:17:11.599 --> 00:17:14.640
But we actually ask our server,
give me the image at

00:17:14.640 --> 00:17:16.730
this exact pixel width
and height.

00:17:16.730 --> 00:17:19.630
And then we also ask the server
to do layering and

00:17:19.630 --> 00:17:20.290
compositing.

00:17:20.290 --> 00:17:22.839
So the server can add the little
square and the borders

00:17:22.839 --> 00:17:24.790
and rounded corners
and all that.

00:17:24.790 --> 00:17:27.579
And then, that way, it returns
the exact right image for the

00:17:27.579 --> 00:17:28.830
Android device.

00:17:28.830 --> 00:17:30.770
In the list view there, you
see, again, we're using

00:17:30.770 --> 00:17:34.110
squares with rounded corners.

00:17:34.110 --> 00:17:35.970
I know the Android look is more

00:17:35.970 --> 00:17:37.180
towards full-bleed images.

00:17:37.180 --> 00:17:40.370
And we did try that in some
early iterations.

00:17:40.370 --> 00:17:43.060
We just never could get it to
look quite right for our

00:17:43.060 --> 00:17:45.470
taste, so we went with
the rounded corners.

00:17:45.470 --> 00:17:47.710
I think that's OK.

00:17:47.710 --> 00:17:50.420
No one's really screamed at us
for not doing full-bleed

00:17:50.420 --> 00:17:51.360
images in lists.

00:17:51.360 --> 00:17:55.480
I think you have some
latitude there.

00:17:55.480 --> 00:17:58.540
Launcher shortcuts, we do this
in our Android client.

00:17:58.540 --> 00:18:00.470
We don't do this, obviously,
in our iPhone

00:18:00.470 --> 00:18:02.520
client, because you can't.

00:18:02.520 --> 00:18:03.380
This is really cool, though.

00:18:03.380 --> 00:18:04.730
You can just tap
the icon in the

00:18:04.730 --> 00:18:06.180
upper-right interaction bar.

00:18:06.180 --> 00:18:08.880
And you can add a shortcut to
your favorite merchant.

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:10.370
It puts it on your desktop.

00:18:10.370 --> 00:18:12.400
So there I have a Bacon
Bacon link.

00:18:12.400 --> 00:18:14.840
So now, whenever I'm near the
truck, I can just tap that

00:18:14.840 --> 00:18:18.810
icon and open a tab at the
Bacon Bacon truck.

00:18:18.810 --> 00:18:21.910
We take advantage of Android
Notifications pretty heavily.

00:18:21.910 --> 00:18:25.030
So whenever you have a tab open,
a notification is open.

00:18:25.030 --> 00:18:27.500
So you can take a phone call
while you're waiting in line,

00:18:27.500 --> 00:18:29.480
or browse the web, whatever.

00:18:29.480 --> 00:18:31.240
You can always come
back to your tab.

00:18:31.240 --> 00:18:33.270
And something I'm not showing
here is, once your tab is

00:18:33.270 --> 00:18:35.350
closed, you can leave a tip.

00:18:35.350 --> 00:18:38.640
So you can order your coffee,
drink it, walk away.

00:18:38.640 --> 00:18:40.890
And then, 10 minutes later, you
can pull out your phone

00:18:40.890 --> 00:18:42.266
and say, oh, that was really
great coffee, I

00:18:42.266 --> 00:18:42.870
want to leave a tip.

00:18:42.870 --> 00:18:45.140
And you can do it right
there from your phone.

00:18:45.140 --> 00:18:48.310
Merchants love to get tips.

00:18:48.310 --> 00:18:51.320
So when I saw the keynote the
first day, the very first

00:18:51.320 --> 00:18:54.540
thing I saw, when I saw the
notification enhancements, is

00:18:54.540 --> 00:18:55.830
we should put tipping
in there.

00:18:55.830 --> 00:18:58.760
So I'm really excited about
Jelly Bean and being able to

00:18:58.760 --> 00:19:02.050
take advantage of that even
further than what we do now.

00:19:02.050 --> 00:19:05.680
So for sharing, you
can share cards.

00:19:05.680 --> 00:19:08.880
We use Android's normal
sharing mechanism.

00:19:08.880 --> 00:19:11.520
We don't try to embed a Twitter
log-in into our app

00:19:11.520 --> 00:19:14.840
and a Facebook log-in and
all those stupid things

00:19:14.840 --> 00:19:16.090
that other apps do.

00:19:18.500 --> 00:19:18.825
[APPLAUSE]

00:19:18.825 --> 00:19:20.075
ERIC BURKE: Yeah.

00:19:22.640 --> 00:19:24.850
This actually ends up being more
powerful, because you can

00:19:24.850 --> 00:19:27.200
share with things you
never even imagined.

00:19:27.200 --> 00:19:29.150
Because I have the Bar
Code Scanner app

00:19:29.150 --> 00:19:30.960
installed on my phone--

00:19:30.960 --> 00:19:33.750
I was actually giving
a demo of the app to

00:19:33.750 --> 00:19:35.720
my boss, Jack Dorsey.

00:19:35.720 --> 00:19:37.090
And he looked at it.

00:19:37.090 --> 00:19:39.140
And when I shared something,
he said, what is that?

00:19:39.140 --> 00:19:40.960
Why does it say bar code?

00:19:40.960 --> 00:19:42.510
I was like, I have no idea.

00:19:42.510 --> 00:19:43.950
I've never seen that.

00:19:43.950 --> 00:19:44.740
Let's try it out.

00:19:44.740 --> 00:19:47.600
So I tapped the button, and it
generates this bar code.

00:19:47.600 --> 00:19:49.560
And then he pulls out his
phone, and he scans it.

00:19:49.560 --> 00:19:52.290
And sure enough, I just shared
a card with a bar code.

00:19:52.290 --> 00:19:54.410
And we never wrote a single
line of code to do that.

00:19:54.410 --> 00:19:55.660
So that was pretty amazing.

00:19:57.790 --> 00:19:59.740
And then, just to wrap it up,
if you go to your account

00:19:59.740 --> 00:20:04.060
settings, this looks more like
a stock Holo look and feel.

00:20:04.060 --> 00:20:06.230
This is a visual cue that
you're kind of in the

00:20:06.230 --> 00:20:09.320
underbelly of the app messing
with your account settings.

00:20:09.320 --> 00:20:12.360
So our philosophy at Square
is we want our app to look

00:20:12.360 --> 00:20:15.950
exactly the same on every
single Android phone.

00:20:15.950 --> 00:20:19.200
So we back-ported as
much as possible.

00:20:19.200 --> 00:20:21.440
We actually hired Jake
Wharton, who wrote

00:20:21.440 --> 00:20:23.000
ActionBarSherlock.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:24.690
And it's a great library.

00:20:24.690 --> 00:20:25.177
[APPLAUSE]

00:20:25.177 --> 00:20:26.151
ERIC BURKE: Yes.

