So while you're walking up here,
I'll share an anecdote.

00:22:39.280 --> 00:22:41.810
When we first went away from the
wallet metaphor and went

00:22:41.810 --> 00:22:44.510
to the new design, we actually
had a whole bunch of

00:22:44.510 --> 00:22:47.330
complaints on Google Play.

00:22:47.330 --> 00:22:50.920
People were furious at us for
taking away the wallet.

00:22:50.920 --> 00:22:53.280
They thought we made it look
uglier and more boring.

00:22:53.280 --> 00:22:57.752
So anyway, I think those
people are all wrong.

00:22:57.752 --> 00:22:59.168
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:59.168 --> 00:23:02.030
ERIC BURKE: I think it does go
to show that you can't always

00:23:02.030 --> 00:23:03.530
listen to everybody
who complains.

00:23:03.530 --> 00:23:05.320
No matter what you do, when
you change your design,

00:23:05.320 --> 00:23:06.410
someone's going to complain.

00:23:06.410 --> 00:23:09.730
So anyway, yeah, question.

00:23:09.730 --> 00:23:11.960
AUDIENCE: Nice design.

00:23:11.960 --> 00:23:17.020
Did you take in account, by
doing the cards, any form of

00:23:17.020 --> 00:23:21.320
sharing of payments
into account?

00:23:21.320 --> 00:23:22.590
ERIC BURKE: Sharing--

00:23:22.590 --> 00:23:24.510
so right now, when you
share, you just share

00:23:24.510 --> 00:23:26.870
a link to the merchant.

00:23:26.870 --> 00:23:29.760
So we're not doing sharing, like
peer-to-peer payments or

00:23:29.760 --> 00:23:31.130
anything like that.

00:23:31.130 --> 00:23:33.550
Right now, it's strictly
sharing the card.

00:23:33.550 --> 00:23:34.770
Like I went to Sightglass.

00:23:34.770 --> 00:23:37.280
I love their coffee, so I'm
going to Tweet about it.

00:23:37.280 --> 00:23:40.990
So there's an icon
to share it.

00:23:40.990 --> 00:23:43.020
Yeah, in the lower-right, I
can tap that and then it

00:23:43.020 --> 00:23:45.330
brings up the Share Action
Provider menu.

00:23:45.330 --> 00:23:46.988
So yeah.

00:23:46.988 --> 00:23:48.690
AUDIENCE: OK, thank you.

00:23:48.690 --> 00:23:49.520
MARCO PAGLIA: Yeah.

00:23:49.520 --> 00:23:51.650
And particularly this screen,
I think, is very interesting

00:23:51.650 --> 00:23:54.870
how the Square guys, they
have embedded all

00:23:54.870 --> 00:23:58.440
actions in this card.

00:23:58.440 --> 00:24:01.295
It just feels so natural to have
actions embedded directly

00:24:01.295 --> 00:24:04.780
in the view, rather than in
the action bar right here.

00:24:04.780 --> 00:24:06.480
Having an action bar, obviously,
doesn't mean that

00:24:06.480 --> 00:24:07.930
all the actions have
to be there.

00:24:07.930 --> 00:24:08.720
It really depends on the view.

00:24:08.720 --> 00:24:12.600
ERIC BURKE: We struggled a
lot with that, actually.

00:24:12.600 --> 00:24:14.670
Early iterations put more
in the action bar.

00:24:14.670 --> 00:24:15.705
But then it would go
into overflow.

00:24:15.705 --> 00:24:19.300
And we just found that people
didn't discover things, if

00:24:19.300 --> 00:24:21.680
they're not right there,
visible on the screen.

00:24:21.680 --> 00:24:24.236
So that's been something we've
iterated on a lot.

00:24:24.236 --> 00:24:25.980
Yeah.

00:24:25.980 --> 00:24:26.245
Question?

00:24:26.245 --> 00:24:27.890
AUDIENCE: Hey, how's it going?

00:24:27.890 --> 00:24:30.830
So I'm curious if you ended up
factoring in some customer

00:24:30.830 --> 00:24:36.310
usability studies, or any work
like that, into your UI design

00:24:36.310 --> 00:24:39.772
as you were evolving it.

00:24:39.772 --> 00:24:40.830
ERIC BURKE: No.

00:24:40.830 --> 00:24:44.029
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:44.029 --> 00:24:45.790
ERIC BURKE: I wish we would
do more of that.

00:24:45.790 --> 00:24:48.590
One thing we do, we do have
a customer insights group.

00:24:48.590 --> 00:24:52.050
And their whole job is to
meet with merchants.

00:24:52.050 --> 00:24:55.170
And they do a lot of
observations of the payment

00:24:55.170 --> 00:24:55.740
experience.

00:24:55.740 --> 00:24:57.120
And they talk to people.

00:24:57.120 --> 00:25:01.370
But we're not really doing
formal usability studies yet.

00:25:01.370 --> 00:25:03.980
And I'm hoping I can help
make that happen.

00:25:03.980 --> 00:25:05.680
I think it's something
we should do more of.

00:25:05.680 --> 00:25:06.870
But right now, no.

00:25:06.870 --> 00:25:07.511
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:25:07.511 --> 00:25:07.640
Cool.

00:25:07.640 --> 00:25:08.020
Thanks.

00:25:08.020 --> 00:25:08.356
ERIC BURKE: Yep.

00:25:08.356 --> 00:25:09.760
MARCO PAGLIA: We'll take
two more questions,

00:25:09.760 --> 00:25:11.365
and then we go ahead.

00:25:11.365 --> 00:25:13.640
AUDIENCE: Maybe a little
bit technical question.

00:25:13.640 --> 00:25:16.970
I want to ask when do you
fetch for images?

00:25:16.970 --> 00:25:18.990
Are there any kind of
pre-fetching on the

00:25:18.990 --> 00:25:20.486
backgrounds maybe?

00:25:20.486 --> 00:25:23.650
ERIC BURKE: So the question is,
when do we fetch images?

00:25:23.650 --> 00:25:28.200
So that's a tough engineering
problem that we're putting a

00:25:28.200 --> 00:25:31.310
lot of emphasis on for the next
release, probably, is to

00:25:31.310 --> 00:25:34.290
do a lot more caching.

00:25:34.290 --> 00:25:36.870
We don't do a tremendous amount
of pre-fetching, but we

00:25:36.870 --> 00:25:38.820
do cache images on
the file system.

00:25:38.820 --> 00:25:41.780
So hopefully, when you come
back, you see the same images.

00:25:41.780 --> 00:25:44.420
And we're investing a lot of
resources to make that even

00:25:44.420 --> 00:25:47.410
better in future versions.

00:25:47.410 --> 00:25:48.740
That's actually been
a very tough

00:25:48.740 --> 00:25:49.990
problem to solve, though.

00:25:53.400 --> 00:25:55.350
AUDIENCE: View one looked
very similar on

00:25:55.350 --> 00:25:57.070
the iPhone and Android.

00:25:57.070 --> 00:25:59.200
And then you switched to having
different looks and

00:25:59.200 --> 00:26:00.780
feels on both platforms.

00:26:00.780 --> 00:26:03.825
Was that a tough brand
decision to make?

00:26:03.825 --> 00:26:05.830
ERIC BURKE: Yeah.

00:26:05.830 --> 00:26:09.030
The philosophy at Square in the
early days was that both

00:26:09.030 --> 00:26:10.990
apps had to look identical.

00:26:10.990 --> 00:26:12.450
And I was never thrilled
with that.

00:26:12.450 --> 00:26:15.710
But we really have two primary
mobile applications.

00:26:15.710 --> 00:26:18.830
We have the payer application
and the seller application.

00:26:18.830 --> 00:26:22.850
So in the seller application,
I am accepting a

00:26:22.850 --> 00:26:23.570
payment from you.

00:26:23.570 --> 00:26:26.000
But at some point, I hand
my phone over to you.

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:28.840
And then you sign your signature
on the screen.

00:26:28.840 --> 00:26:31.040
So in the seller app, it's
actually more important to

00:26:31.040 --> 00:26:32.850
have consistency across
platforms.

00:26:32.850 --> 00:26:35.640
Because if I'm buying something
and I walk up to you

00:26:35.640 --> 00:26:38.500
and I'm signing my name and
giving you my credit card, I

00:26:38.500 --> 00:26:40.770
want that application
to be trustworthy.

00:26:40.770 --> 00:26:43.450
So I need it to look
consistent.

00:26:43.450 --> 00:26:46.000
From the payer experience,
though, this is my phone and I

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:46.990
never give it to anybody else.

00:26:46.990 --> 00:26:49.290
And I'm in Android
all day long.

00:26:49.290 --> 00:26:51.820
So in the payer experience, we
have flexibility to be more

00:26:51.820 --> 00:26:55.230
creative on the different
platforms and we can diverge a

00:26:55.230 --> 00:26:55.960
little bit.

00:26:55.960 --> 00:26:56.420
It was funny.

00:26:56.420 --> 00:26:59.830
One of the engineers made the
comment when we were first

00:26:59.830 --> 00:27:02.740
going through this, he was
like, you know, what's

00:27:02.740 --> 00:27:05.630
actually happening is our iPhone
client is becoming more

00:27:05.630 --> 00:27:07.300
like an Android application.

00:27:07.300 --> 00:27:10.000
Because they went with a lot of
the full-bleed images also,

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:13.710
and it made the iPhone client
look more like Android.

00:27:13.710 --> 00:27:16.930
But yeah, because of the
audience, we feel like we can

00:27:16.930 --> 00:27:19.810
make each app look a little
bit more different on the

00:27:19.810 --> 00:27:21.452
different platforms.

00:27:21.452 --> 00:27:21.844
Yep.

00:27:21.844 --> 00:27:22.630
MARCO PAGLIA: OK.

00:27:22.630 --> 00:27:24.290
And on this great
question, let's

00:27:24.290 --> 00:27:25.000
give a round of applause.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:26.000
ERIC BURKE: Thank you.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:31.000
[APPLAUSE]

