MICHAEL NOVAK: We rock
Google Docs.

00:28:09.340 --> 00:28:11.950
So as Marco said, we're GigBeat,
which is a concert

00:28:11.950 --> 00:28:13.200
application for Android.

00:28:13.200 --> 00:28:15.330
It helps you find when your
favorite artists are going to

00:28:15.330 --> 00:28:16.580
be in your city.

00:28:19.590 --> 00:28:20.260
You'll actually need to be--

00:28:20.260 --> 00:28:21.230
GUENTHER BEYER: Go ahead?

00:28:21.230 --> 00:28:22.674
MICHAEL NOVAK: No,
it's all you.

00:28:22.674 --> 00:28:23.880
Yes.

00:28:23.880 --> 00:28:26.140
So it lets you find out.

00:28:26.140 --> 00:28:29.460
So it's great to go to shows,
but I found myself missing

00:28:29.460 --> 00:28:32.470
shows all the time, just not
finding out about it until

00:28:32.470 --> 00:28:34.590
somebody says, you missed an
amazing show last night.

00:28:34.590 --> 00:28:35.550
I don't know why you
weren't there.

00:28:35.550 --> 00:28:38.280
It's like, thanks,
for inviting me.

00:28:38.280 --> 00:28:41.150
So I decided to solve that
problem by creating the

00:28:41.150 --> 00:28:44.150
application that would let me
follow my artists and know

00:28:44.150 --> 00:28:47.500
when they're going to actually
be in my city well before even

00:28:47.500 --> 00:28:49.580
tickets usually sometimes
go on sale.

00:28:49.580 --> 00:28:54.720
And it lets us really get
excited about shows.

00:28:54.720 --> 00:28:57.794
So yeah, that's GigBeat.

00:28:57.794 --> 00:29:00.000
GUENTHER BEYER: We want to show
a couple of patterns that

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:02.550
we introduced to GigBeat,
because it has about six

00:29:02.550 --> 00:29:04.300
months of evolution behind it.

00:29:04.300 --> 00:29:07.570
And I think the first one
might be branding.

00:29:07.570 --> 00:29:09.390
Branding is always tough,
because on one side, you have

00:29:09.390 --> 00:29:11.360
to create something
that stands out.

00:29:11.360 --> 00:29:14.340
On the other hand, you have to
create something that feels

00:29:14.340 --> 00:29:15.610
just right in the ecosystem.

00:29:15.610 --> 00:29:18.040
So these two things are fighting
against each other a

00:29:18.040 --> 00:29:19.100
little bit.

00:29:19.100 --> 00:29:23.320
And we tried a lot of things,
from Captain America to

00:29:23.320 --> 00:29:26.250
audio-like icons, every
kind of shape.

00:29:26.250 --> 00:29:30.780
But finally, we just settled on
the initials GB, because we

00:29:30.780 --> 00:29:31.730
really like the name.

00:29:31.730 --> 00:29:34.930
And we felt that this
just is enough.

00:29:34.930 --> 00:29:38.180
At the top one, we can see the
first icon that we ever

00:29:38.180 --> 00:29:41.730
created that had some kind
of a final touch to it.

00:29:41.730 --> 00:29:43.990
And then you see how the
icon evolved over time.

00:29:43.990 --> 00:29:47.690
And right now, it's pretty much
100% like an Ice Cream

00:29:47.690 --> 00:29:50.120
Sandwich, Jelly Bean icon.

00:29:50.120 --> 00:29:53.840
So it's a similar thing
with color.

00:29:53.840 --> 00:29:56.660
Android is about simplicity,
or beauty and

00:29:56.660 --> 00:29:58.690
simplicity, more or less.

00:29:58.690 --> 00:30:02.040
And you don't want to have a
lot of colors fighting for

00:30:02.040 --> 00:30:03.960
attention, fighting against
each other.

00:30:03.960 --> 00:30:06.860
So we just went with basic black
tones, gray tones and

00:30:06.860 --> 00:30:09.890
obviously, a couple of white
tones for the phones.

00:30:09.890 --> 00:30:12.710
And we are highlighting really
special parts about the

00:30:12.710 --> 00:30:15.200
application with this pink,
which is obviously our

00:30:15.200 --> 00:30:16.680
branding color.

00:30:16.680 --> 00:30:19.465
For example, in that list, you
can see a couple of gigs that

00:30:19.465 --> 00:30:21.570
are, more or less, interesting
for you from the

00:30:21.570 --> 00:30:22.600
bands that you love.

00:30:22.600 --> 00:30:25.400
And they also had one particular
pink line.

00:30:25.400 --> 00:30:27.990
That is a gig that is showing
up really close to where you

00:30:27.990 --> 00:30:28.550
are right now.

00:30:28.550 --> 00:30:31.560
So you probably have more of an
interest than all the other

00:30:31.560 --> 00:30:34.270
gigs to you.

00:30:34.270 --> 00:30:37.020
So I wanted to talk a little
bit about topography, but I

00:30:37.020 --> 00:30:39.380
think Mike has a better
shirt for that part.

00:30:39.380 --> 00:30:39.825
MICHAEL NOVAK: Yeah.

00:30:39.825 --> 00:30:41.816
I kind of like topography.

00:30:41.816 --> 00:30:45.310
So yeah, with GigBeat, in our
early versions, we were really

00:30:45.310 --> 00:30:45.890
all over the place.

00:30:45.890 --> 00:30:48.110
We had lots of different kind
of designs, different

00:30:48.110 --> 00:30:50.040
elements, different buttons.

00:30:50.040 --> 00:30:53.270
And it was kind of
wacky, I think.

00:30:53.270 --> 00:30:55.340
And we started with the
Eurofurence font up front.

00:30:55.340 --> 00:30:57.150
We used this, really,
mostly in headers.

00:30:57.150 --> 00:30:59.020
So you can see the top artist
is the only artist that

00:30:59.020 --> 00:31:00.710
actually has that font.

00:31:00.710 --> 00:31:02.020
And we didn't want
to overuse it.

00:31:02.020 --> 00:31:04.520
But we also wanted to get a
little bit of depth into the

00:31:04.520 --> 00:31:07.210
application, so we thought
that might work.

00:31:07.210 --> 00:31:09.340
But then we realized we were
having some spacing issues.

00:31:09.340 --> 00:31:11.440
We realized that letters were
sometimes showing up on top of

00:31:11.440 --> 00:31:11.850
each other.

00:31:11.850 --> 00:31:14.630
Rendering wasn't working,
really, that great for us, so

00:31:14.630 --> 00:31:16.180
we decided to try
another font.

00:31:16.180 --> 00:31:19.650
And also the same thing, really,
just a really annoying

00:31:19.650 --> 00:31:21.310
problem of rendering.

00:31:21.310 --> 00:31:23.190
It really messed with our user
experience, we thought,

00:31:23.190 --> 00:31:25.630
because it's important to
see that information.

00:31:25.630 --> 00:31:28.220
And if that information is
obscured in any way, it's no

00:31:28.220 --> 00:31:29.470
longer relevant for you.

00:31:32.470 --> 00:31:35.950
Before Roboto was available,
we decided to use the Droid

00:31:35.950 --> 00:31:39.070
Sans as much as possible and,
really, just play around with

00:31:39.070 --> 00:31:40.650
the different weights
that were available

00:31:40.650 --> 00:31:42.300
to give some depth.

00:31:42.300 --> 00:31:44.110
And then, when Roboto
came out, we were so

00:31:44.110 --> 00:31:45.290
excited about it.

00:31:45.290 --> 00:31:47.060
I'm actually wearing
a Roboto shirt.

00:31:47.060 --> 00:31:48.730
We were really excited
about it.

00:31:48.730 --> 00:31:51.230
And we decided to just
switch to using

00:31:51.230 --> 00:31:53.480
it as much as possible.

00:31:53.480 --> 00:31:57.420
You can see we use some
different weights.

00:31:57.420 --> 00:31:59.430
The headline font for the list
item is actually a little bit

00:31:59.430 --> 00:32:01.390
larger than some of
the other ones.

00:32:01.390 --> 00:32:03.190
You'll see on some other slides
we've got some other

00:32:03.190 --> 00:32:04.690
really creative ways
we use it.

00:32:07.190 --> 00:32:08.437
A dashboard.

00:32:08.437 --> 00:32:10.720
Dashboard's a really interesting
pattern.

00:32:10.720 --> 00:32:13.685
You've seen it used throughout
Android for a

00:32:13.685 --> 00:32:14.670
little while now.

00:32:14.670 --> 00:32:20.950
And we tried to figure out how
to use it and be unique.

00:32:20.950 --> 00:32:24.510
We wanted to really emphasize
our brand as much as possible.

00:32:24.510 --> 00:32:29.950
And the pink is really the
center of it, which is--

00:32:29.950 --> 00:32:32.100
I'm color blind, so
that actually does

00:32:32.100 --> 00:32:33.600
look pink to me, though.

00:32:33.600 --> 00:32:36.280
And the icons are
really unique.

00:32:36.280 --> 00:32:39.900
We made sure that we spent lots
of time going over each

00:32:39.900 --> 00:32:42.390
individual icon to make sure
they really represented each

00:32:42.390 --> 00:32:44.760
section in the best
way possible.

00:32:44.760 --> 00:32:47.680
We don't want to drive you to
an artist list when you care

00:32:47.680 --> 00:32:51.290
more about locations, or when
you care about artists, seeing

00:32:51.290 --> 00:32:53.690
what's all around you right
when you open up the

00:32:53.690 --> 00:32:54.560
application.

00:32:54.560 --> 00:32:56.870
So we felt, with the amount of
content that we had for the

00:32:56.870 --> 00:32:58.120
application, the dashboard
would work

00:32:58.120 --> 00:32:59.790
really, really well.

00:32:59.790 --> 00:33:01.040
And it also is unique.

00:33:01.040 --> 00:33:04.010
We actually, for Mobile World
Congress, had pins made up of

00:33:04.010 --> 00:33:06.710
all our dashboard icons, which
was really neat because you

00:33:06.710 --> 00:33:08.900
can actually associate the brand
with the part of the app

00:33:08.900 --> 00:33:12.530
that, for the most, you'd see
as just pretty basic.

00:33:12.530 --> 00:33:15.090
But then, going to the tablet,
we realized, well, you can't

00:33:15.090 --> 00:33:18.180
just put four big buttons
onto a 10-inch screen.

00:33:18.180 --> 00:33:19.520
That doesn't really work.

00:33:19.520 --> 00:33:22.360
So we decided to add as
much fresh content

00:33:22.360 --> 00:33:23.530
as we possibly could.

00:33:23.530 --> 00:33:27.150
And that's where we decided to
use the larger images to

00:33:27.150 --> 00:33:29.810
really bring some color to it,
but also bring some relevant

00:33:29.810 --> 00:33:31.116
information.

