MICHAEL NOVAK: It
looks pretty.

00:33:42.560 --> 00:33:42.980
So yeah.

00:33:42.980 --> 00:33:44.920
I mean, we didn't actually get
to the dashboard in the

00:33:44.920 --> 00:33:45.940
initial version.

00:33:45.940 --> 00:33:47.990
The version you see on the left
is a really old version

00:33:47.990 --> 00:33:50.540
of the application that has
three tabs with a little

00:33:50.540 --> 00:33:52.030
pointer at the bottom.

00:33:52.030 --> 00:33:53.270
We were kind of all
over the place.

00:33:53.270 --> 00:33:54.440
There's some textures
in there.

00:33:54.440 --> 00:33:57.000
And you have to do a lot
of clicking too.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:33:58.970
There's some buttons there that
just don't really feel

00:33:58.970 --> 00:34:00.840
like they're part of the UI.

00:34:00.840 --> 00:34:02.650
Especially, what happens when
that list scrolls up?

00:34:02.650 --> 00:34:04.290
All those buttons go away.

00:34:04.290 --> 00:34:05.870
So we really wanted
to simplify it.

00:34:05.870 --> 00:34:07.060
And so that's how we
ended up coming

00:34:07.060 --> 00:34:08.139
to our current dashboard.

00:34:08.139 --> 00:34:10.710
We're like, let's really focus
on what are the most important

00:34:10.710 --> 00:34:13.630
pieces of our application and
give users the option to dive

00:34:13.630 --> 00:34:15.909
into each one of those
as they wish.

00:34:19.090 --> 00:34:21.480
ViewPager, it's awesome.

00:34:21.480 --> 00:34:24.610
So ViewPager works really well
for us on the phone.

00:34:24.610 --> 00:34:27.700
When you click on the Artists
icon from the dashboard, you

00:34:27.700 --> 00:34:29.460
get presented with
the list view.

00:34:29.460 --> 00:34:31.460
You get to see all your artists
up front, which is

00:34:31.460 --> 00:34:33.969
every artist that you follow
inside the application.

00:34:33.969 --> 00:34:36.040
You swipe to the right,
you can see Last.fm

00:34:36.040 --> 00:34:38.590
recommendations, if you're
a Last.fm user.

00:34:38.590 --> 00:34:40.199
And when you swipe to the
left, you actually

00:34:40.199 --> 00:34:41.520
see what's near you.

00:34:41.520 --> 00:34:43.770
So it basically just cuts out
all of the artists that are

00:34:43.770 --> 00:34:45.980
not going to be in your city.

00:34:45.980 --> 00:34:48.600
And you basically could see your
entire artist collection,

00:34:48.600 --> 00:34:51.409
just by swiping up and down,
left and right, throughout the

00:34:51.409 --> 00:34:51.949
entire list.

00:34:51.949 --> 00:34:53.800
It feels really great.

00:34:53.800 --> 00:34:56.440
And when we went to the tablet,
it didn't exactly work

00:34:56.440 --> 00:34:58.150
the same way, because then you
didn't want just really big

00:34:58.150 --> 00:34:59.610
lists all over the place.

00:34:59.610 --> 00:35:02.760
So we decided to use bigger
images again and do a grid

00:35:02.760 --> 00:35:03.670
view with--

00:35:03.670 --> 00:35:06.620
what you can't really see on the
phone is a filtered list.

00:35:06.620 --> 00:35:08.720
So you could actually
filter through.

00:35:08.720 --> 00:35:11.360
We actually list out the
services, so you could just

00:35:11.360 --> 00:35:14.150
see what you have from RDO, what
you have from Last.fm.

00:35:14.150 --> 00:35:17.920
It gives you some
options there.

00:35:17.920 --> 00:35:19.780
Location, location
was really fun.

00:35:19.780 --> 00:35:22.480
That took us a while, too.

00:35:22.480 --> 00:35:25.740
This is also something we just
didn't get right, which--

00:35:25.740 --> 00:35:28.090
it's actually OK to not get
things right the first time.

00:35:28.090 --> 00:35:30.090
You really learn a lot from
the whole process.

00:35:30.090 --> 00:35:33.520
So it was definitely a learning
process for us.

00:35:33.520 --> 00:35:35.230
We have some buttons.

00:35:35.230 --> 00:35:37.730
Like you can click a button to
get information that's near

00:35:37.730 --> 00:35:41.120
you, which, for us, felt really
awkward, because we can

00:35:41.120 --> 00:35:43.710
actually get access to the
GPS and just start

00:35:43.710 --> 00:35:44.680
loading data for you.

00:35:44.680 --> 00:35:47.430
So why should we have to wait
for you to click the button?

00:35:47.430 --> 00:35:48.920
And then also the same
thing for a search.

00:35:48.920 --> 00:35:50.510
It was just tucked
right next to it.

00:35:50.510 --> 00:35:51.760
And you had to search
for a city.

00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:53.910
And this list view would
actually be empty, if you

00:35:53.910 --> 00:35:56.130
didn't have any content already
searched for in the

00:35:56.130 --> 00:36:00.340
application, which is
also very useful.

00:36:00.340 --> 00:36:02.150
So we tried to do some
improvements here.

00:36:02.150 --> 00:36:05.695
We added a Search bar, for some
reason, in the screen at

00:36:05.695 --> 00:36:06.730
the top of the list.

00:36:06.730 --> 00:36:08.640
And then we just decided it
would be really awesome if you

00:36:08.640 --> 00:36:11.690
could favorite some of
these locations.

00:36:11.690 --> 00:36:13.510
If you're not somebody that
travels very often, you're

00:36:13.510 --> 00:36:16.130
going to go back to the same
location over and over again.

00:36:16.130 --> 00:36:17.830
So we figured it would be great
to have those right on

00:36:17.830 --> 00:36:20.485
the first screen of the Location
section to really get

00:36:20.485 --> 00:36:21.960
some easy access.

00:36:21.960 --> 00:36:24.750
But it's really empty, if you
don't have any favorites.

00:36:24.750 --> 00:36:27.590
You still have to do something
to get content.

00:36:27.590 --> 00:36:30.860
So what we decided to do, after
lots of debate, was how

00:36:30.860 --> 00:36:33.710
do we get nearby information
and favorite information

00:36:33.710 --> 00:36:36.280
together on a screen so that
they could provide as much

00:36:36.280 --> 00:36:38.720
useful information without
much interaction?

00:36:38.720 --> 00:36:40.770
So we decided, let's pin
the favorites up to

00:36:40.770 --> 00:36:41.700
the top of the screen.

00:36:41.700 --> 00:36:44.676
And you'll always have
easy access to those.

00:36:44.676 --> 00:36:46.160
Those are definitely very
important to you.

00:36:46.160 --> 00:36:47.950
But if you've never used the
app before or maybe you

00:36:47.950 --> 00:36:50.600
haven't favorited anything yet,
you can still get nearby

00:36:50.600 --> 00:36:51.650
information as well.

00:36:51.650 --> 00:36:52.480
Or you could be traveling.

00:36:52.480 --> 00:36:53.560
Like we're in San Francisco.

00:36:53.560 --> 00:36:55.830
So most of my favorites
are in New York.

00:36:55.830 --> 00:36:58.000
But if I open up the Location
screen, I can start to see

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:00.530
venues from San Francisco
because it's near by me.

00:37:00.530 --> 00:37:02.510
And we were able to do that
all with a segment list.

00:37:02.510 --> 00:37:03.820
We were able to create
different sections.

00:37:03.820 --> 00:37:07.640
And we thought that that was
the awesome solution out of

00:37:07.640 --> 00:37:10.271
all the other ones we were
throwing around.

00:37:10.271 --> 00:37:14.900
GUENTHER BEYER: Speaking of
empty screens, you will have

00:37:14.900 --> 00:37:16.310
to deal with empty screens
eventually.

00:37:16.310 --> 00:37:18.550
There are a lot of apps that are
loading content from the

00:37:18.550 --> 00:37:20.880
web and, at times, you just
don't have a web connection.

00:37:20.880 --> 00:37:25.040
So how do you deal with
empty screens?

00:37:25.040 --> 00:37:27.260
This was the first iteration
of GigBeat's empty screens.

00:37:27.260 --> 00:37:29.270
And to be honest, they are
really, really boring and not

00:37:29.270 --> 00:37:30.080
really informative.

00:37:30.080 --> 00:37:33.110
And we have a lot of those.

00:37:33.110 --> 00:37:36.770
And actually we decided that,
if you can't really inform--

00:37:36.770 --> 00:37:38.810
because that is obviously what
you want to do in such an

00:37:38.810 --> 00:37:39.660
application--

00:37:39.660 --> 00:37:41.800
at least entertain to
a certain extent.

00:37:41.800 --> 00:37:45.530
You want to have your users
stay within the app and at

00:37:45.530 --> 00:37:48.000
least enjoy the empty screens,
even though they aren't really

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:48.900
that beautiful.

00:37:48.900 --> 00:37:51.470
And so we created a couple of
really small illustrations and

00:37:51.470 --> 00:37:54.250
tried to improve the copy and
just tried to give a certain

00:37:54.250 --> 00:37:57.420
feeling across it, a little bit
of fun in between, while

00:37:57.420 --> 00:37:59.610
information is loading or while
they have to access some

00:37:59.610 --> 00:38:02.390
kind of a log-in or anything
like that.

00:38:02.390 --> 00:38:06.900
So we think these turned out
pretty nicely in the overall

00:38:06.900 --> 00:38:08.305
context of the application.

00:38:08.305 --> 00:38:09.890
MICHAEL NOVAK: The other really
awesome thing we added

00:38:09.890 --> 00:38:11.680
was we added some actions
at the bottom.

00:38:11.680 --> 00:38:14.190
So when you're on the empty
screen of Last.fm and you

00:38:14.190 --> 00:38:15.770
haven't either logged-in
or you don't have any

00:38:15.770 --> 00:38:17.760
recommendations, it will
actually say, hey, you can

00:38:17.760 --> 00:38:18.470
log-in to Last.fm.

00:38:18.470 --> 00:38:20.830
And this screen will populate
with some artists.

00:38:20.830 --> 00:38:23.020
So we really tried to take
advantage of as much of the

00:38:23.020 --> 00:38:26.570
screen as possible to make it
easy for the user to actually

00:38:26.570 --> 00:38:30.305
get benefit from that screen.

00:38:30.305 --> 00:38:31.585
GUENTHER BEYER: That's
yours, right?

00:38:31.585 --> 00:38:32.460
MICHAEL NOVAK: Right.

00:38:32.460 --> 00:38:33.500
Notifications.

00:38:33.500 --> 00:38:37.240
So GigBeat, obviously, does a
lot of work for you when you

00:38:37.240 --> 00:38:39.890
don't use the application.

00:38:39.890 --> 00:38:42.340
But one of the interesting
things that we were playing

00:38:42.340 --> 00:38:45.020
with, especially when we were
doing bigger releases, was how

00:38:45.020 --> 00:38:48.010
do we let the user know
there's new content?

00:38:48.010 --> 00:38:51.670
You might not actually update
the application the first time

00:38:51.670 --> 00:38:53.440
you-- you might not use the
application the first

00:38:53.440 --> 00:38:54.910
time you update it.

00:38:54.910 --> 00:38:57.510
So it could be days or weeks
before you actually

00:38:57.510 --> 00:38:58.830
venture into it.

00:38:58.830 --> 00:39:00.270
In most cases, you'll
venture into it

00:39:00.270 --> 00:39:01.020
because you have a need.

00:39:01.020 --> 00:39:02.740
You're trying to get
to certain content.

00:39:02.740 --> 00:39:05.220
So we didn't want to just pop
up a dialogue or pop up a

00:39:05.220 --> 00:39:07.250
screen that says,
hey, what's new?

00:39:07.250 --> 00:39:09.410
By the way, thanks for
using the app.

00:39:09.410 --> 00:39:16.130
We wanted to really be as
unobtrusive as possible.

00:39:16.130 --> 00:39:18.180
So you can go to
the next slide.

00:39:18.180 --> 00:39:23.130
So what we were doing was we'd
actually pop up a notification

00:39:23.130 --> 00:39:24.185
for major releases.

00:39:24.185 --> 00:39:26.400
I want to emphasize major
releases, because bug fix

00:39:26.400 --> 00:39:28.100
updates, like getting a
notification every time you

00:39:28.100 --> 00:39:30.890
open the app would be kind
of annoying, I think.

00:39:30.890 --> 00:39:32.740
So we wanted to make sure that
we were definitely doing this

00:39:32.740 --> 00:39:34.320
just for major--

00:39:34.320 --> 00:39:36.040
we've got new features that
we definitely think

00:39:36.040 --> 00:39:37.360
you're going to love.

00:39:37.360 --> 00:39:39.200
So when you first open the
application, instead of

00:39:39.200 --> 00:39:41.610
actually getting in your way and
showing you that Welcome

00:39:41.610 --> 00:39:44.330
screen first, we actually just
leave the app the way it is

00:39:44.330 --> 00:39:45.390
and pop the notification up.

00:39:45.390 --> 00:39:47.580
So that way, once you're done
looking for whatever it is you

00:39:47.580 --> 00:39:50.360
came into the app to look for,
you can actually, at your

00:39:50.360 --> 00:39:52.490
leisure, check out what we've
got that's new in our

00:39:52.490 --> 00:39:54.802
application.

00:39:54.802 --> 00:39:57.710
GUENTHER BEYER: We might add
that you have to create about

00:39:57.710 --> 00:40:00.910
four sizes and three different
styles for every notification

00:40:00.910 --> 00:40:01.890
icon that you are creating.

00:40:01.890 --> 00:40:04.050
So be prepared.

00:40:04.050 --> 00:40:06.080
MICHAEL NOVAK: This is actually
my favorite feature

00:40:06.080 --> 00:40:08.490
that we added in our latest
release that's

00:40:08.490 --> 00:40:10.100
on the market today.

00:40:10.100 --> 00:40:13.300
We do playback notifications.

00:40:13.300 --> 00:40:17.830
So concerts is music, but you're
not always at concerts.

00:40:17.830 --> 00:40:21.170
You're listening to music
on the go, commuting.

00:40:21.170 --> 00:40:24.750
So it's awesome to find out
about the artist that you're

00:40:24.750 --> 00:40:26.830
actually listening to when
you're listening to it.

00:40:26.830 --> 00:40:30.570
So what we do here is we pop
up a silent notification

00:40:30.570 --> 00:40:33.020
during playback, if that artist
is actually going to be

00:40:33.020 --> 00:40:33.990
in your city.

00:40:33.990 --> 00:40:37.020
And we do it silently because
the worst thing in the world

00:40:37.020 --> 00:40:40.440
would be to pop up a
notification about some

00:40:40.440 --> 00:40:43.940
secondary data for the artist
and cause a little beep in the

00:40:43.940 --> 00:40:45.040
middle of the song.

00:40:45.040 --> 00:40:46.260
That would just frustrate me.

00:40:46.260 --> 00:40:49.180
So we wanted to make sure that
we provided the information so

00:40:49.180 --> 00:40:52.590
that the user would be notified
that the artist is

00:40:52.590 --> 00:40:53.240
coming to their city.

00:40:53.240 --> 00:40:55.120
But we didn't want to interrupt
the actual process

00:40:55.120 --> 00:40:57.290
that they're doing, which is
listening to the music.

00:40:57.290 --> 00:41:00.040
So yeah, we were definitely
being polite, silent

00:41:00.040 --> 00:41:01.210
notifications.

00:41:01.210 --> 00:41:03.990
And you get the information
without being bothered.

00:41:07.750 --> 00:41:09.950
Event details.

00:41:09.950 --> 00:41:13.060
So event details
is interesting.

00:41:13.060 --> 00:41:13.990
You've got the venue.

00:41:13.990 --> 00:41:15.650
They've got the date,
the time, tickets.

00:41:15.650 --> 00:41:18.870
It's pretty basic information,
for the most part.

00:41:18.870 --> 00:41:20.960
And in our first couple
of iterations,

00:41:20.960 --> 00:41:21.810
it was really boring.

00:41:21.810 --> 00:41:22.980
We just did a lot of text.

00:41:22.980 --> 00:41:24.680
There wasn't really much
breakup in the UI.

00:41:24.680 --> 00:41:26.270
There wasn't much color.

00:41:26.270 --> 00:41:28.780
I mean, there was really a
lot of the basic colors.

00:41:28.780 --> 00:41:30.770
So we decided let's
stick an avatar in

00:41:30.770 --> 00:41:33.530
there for the headliner.

00:41:33.530 --> 00:41:36.940
And let's throw some icons into
the list to really break

00:41:36.940 --> 00:41:38.210
up the flow of all the text.

00:41:38.210 --> 00:41:39.320
But it still didn't
seem right.

00:41:39.320 --> 00:41:43.320
It felt like it was just
a lot of empty--

00:41:43.320 --> 00:41:44.240
the space didn't work for me.

00:41:44.240 --> 00:41:47.340
I didn't like this version
very much.

00:41:47.340 --> 00:41:49.760
But what you see is
we actually--

00:41:49.760 --> 00:41:51.010
go to the next slide---

00:41:52.910 --> 00:41:56.110
what you actually see
is bigger pictures.

00:41:56.110 --> 00:41:57.140
I love this screen.

00:41:57.140 --> 00:41:57.920
This is one of my favorites.

00:41:57.920 --> 00:42:00.440
I think I stared at this screen
for 20 minutes when we

00:42:00.440 --> 00:42:02.090
actually got it running.

00:42:02.090 --> 00:42:03.130
It was amazing.

00:42:03.130 --> 00:42:05.750
And so we did a nice
large photo for the

00:42:05.750 --> 00:42:06.980
headliner of the event.

00:42:06.980 --> 00:42:10.540
And then we added in the
supporting artists as well.

00:42:10.540 --> 00:42:13.450
So you'll actually get two
photos there, if there's only

00:42:13.450 --> 00:42:14.400
three artists playing.

00:42:14.400 --> 00:42:17.810
And then, if there's any more
than three artists, we'll use

00:42:17.810 --> 00:42:19.875
that other space to allow
you to click through to

00:42:19.875 --> 00:42:20.990
see the full list.

00:42:20.990 --> 00:42:24.860
But the event date is actually
really awesome, because this

00:42:24.860 --> 00:42:28.360
is where we were able to use
various weights of Roboto to

00:42:28.360 --> 00:42:33.060
really drive the emphasis on
the date, where we do the

00:42:33.060 --> 00:42:37.710
actual day in a large, thinner
font, and then the rest of the

00:42:37.710 --> 00:42:40.500
date in a smaller,
bolder font.

00:42:40.500 --> 00:42:43.670
Which was a nice break up from
the other text that comes

00:42:43.670 --> 00:42:45.080
below the photos.

00:42:45.080 --> 00:42:47.560
We were able to put the venue
information, check-in

00:42:47.560 --> 00:42:50.140
capabilities, and
getting tickets.

00:42:50.140 --> 00:42:54.350
And then, on the tablet screen,
we had some room to

00:42:54.350 --> 00:42:57.250
throw some more photos in,
some more information.

00:42:57.250 --> 00:42:58.900
And we actually had the list
right on the side, so you

00:42:58.900 --> 00:43:02.050
could just go through each of
the different events and see

00:43:02.050 --> 00:43:04.486
the information right
next to it.

00:43:04.486 --> 00:43:05.680
GUENTHER BEYER: If you're
thinking about this

00:43:05.680 --> 00:43:08.100
application, I think this
is about events.

00:43:08.100 --> 00:43:09.150
This is about live music.

00:43:09.150 --> 00:43:11.980
And live music is
exciting, right?

00:43:11.980 --> 00:43:14.550
These screens were not
really that exciting.

00:43:14.550 --> 00:43:15.800
They're pretty boring.

00:43:15.800 --> 00:43:16.790
But I think we figured
it out pretty

00:43:16.790 --> 00:43:17.640
nicely with these screens.

00:43:17.640 --> 00:43:19.540
Because these photos, they
actually are exciting.

00:43:19.540 --> 00:43:23.570
You actually want to see
these guys live, right?

00:43:23.570 --> 00:43:25.110
OK, the next one's the
artist details.

00:43:25.110 --> 00:43:29.050
And I think you will love this
one as well, because the old

00:43:29.050 --> 00:43:32.200
version of GigBeat, it just had
a list of-- well, it had

00:43:32.200 --> 00:43:34.300
the artist name and
then a list of its

00:43:34.300 --> 00:43:35.610
gigs that were upcoming.

00:43:35.610 --> 00:43:37.750
And we wanted to add a little
bit more to these screens.

00:43:37.750 --> 00:43:42.840
So I sketched up this pretty
rough thing here.

00:43:42.840 --> 00:43:43.640
And I showed it to Mike.

00:43:43.640 --> 00:43:44.510
And he really liked it.

00:43:44.510 --> 00:43:48.480
But he hated it at the same
time, I guess, because--

00:43:48.480 --> 00:43:50.070
fun fact--

00:43:50.070 --> 00:43:52.240
Marco here is the creator of
that BeautifulPeople's

00:43:52.240 --> 00:43:54.520
People's app from Android 4.0.

00:43:54.520 --> 00:43:56.160
And we wanted to do something
similar with

00:43:56.160 --> 00:43:57.650
that carousel slider.

00:43:57.650 --> 00:43:59.470
And they can swipe from
left to right

00:43:59.470 --> 00:44:01.700
and from top to bottom.

00:44:01.700 --> 00:44:03.250
As it turned out, that
code was just

