00:53:13.890 --> 00:53:16.720
I noticed that your application
supports a variety

00:53:16.720 --> 00:53:19.758
of Android versions and also
a wide variety of screen

00:53:19.758 --> 00:53:21.010
resolutions.

00:53:21.010 --> 00:53:23.610
Would you like to share with
us your experiences in

00:53:23.610 --> 00:53:27.650
supporting multiple versions of
Androids and also different

00:53:27.650 --> 00:53:28.660
hardware specs?

00:53:28.660 --> 00:53:29.060
Thank you.

00:53:29.060 --> 00:53:29.950
MICHAEL NOVAK: Sure.

00:53:29.950 --> 00:53:33.050
It was certainly a challenge at
the beginning, because we

00:53:33.050 --> 00:53:34.600
were trying to figure
out what all these

00:53:34.600 --> 00:53:36.020
differences really were.

00:53:36.020 --> 00:53:40.480
But what it came down to is
there's a lot of resources

00:53:40.480 --> 00:53:44.400
available to abstract away
some of those different

00:53:44.400 --> 00:53:48.570
nuances, like when things
get deprecated.

00:53:48.570 --> 00:53:51.790
For example, some of the
notification stuff was

00:53:51.790 --> 00:53:53.500
deprecated in how
you create it.

00:53:53.500 --> 00:53:57.950
The action bar is certainly
something that's introduced in

00:53:57.950 --> 00:53:59.600
Honeycomb, and is not available
on Gingerbread.

00:53:59.600 --> 00:54:02.800
So we really tried to abstract
away as much of the resources

00:54:02.800 --> 00:54:07.070
as possible, so we could plug
them in where they made sense.

00:54:07.070 --> 00:54:10.950
Different static classes to
lazy-load APIs that are

00:54:10.950 --> 00:54:15.350
available on newer devices
versus older.

00:54:15.350 --> 00:54:17.370
It's the same thing with layout
resources for different

00:54:17.370 --> 00:54:18.440
screen sizes.

00:54:18.440 --> 00:54:22.170
We took advantage of values
files and the dimensions file

00:54:22.170 --> 00:54:25.180
to actually keep all of our
dimensions there, so that our

00:54:25.180 --> 00:54:26.600
layouts weren't repetitive.

00:54:26.600 --> 00:54:29.240
And that allowed us to scale
pretty easily, without a lot

00:54:29.240 --> 00:54:32.570
of work and testing and really
having to worry about if we

00:54:32.570 --> 00:54:35.900
changed the right file or not
and made the size correct.

00:54:39.844 --> 00:54:40.830
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:54:40.830 --> 00:54:42.309
MICHAEL NOVAK: Sure.

