These are three different taps
displayed in this view.

02:03:26.230 --> 02:03:29.550
And the thing I think is most
interesting to note about

02:03:29.550 --> 02:03:32.280
this, especially after we've
looked at the last two

02:03:32.280 --> 02:03:34.890
screens, is that in the last
two screens, we've got this

02:03:34.890 --> 02:03:37.950
nice, colorful background, we've
got the hand-lettering--

02:03:37.950 --> 02:03:39.270
boom.

02:03:39.270 --> 02:03:41.940
Here we're into something that
feels very frameworky.

02:03:41.940 --> 02:03:45.845
We've got this gray action bar,
we've got the blue tabs,

02:03:45.845 --> 02:03:47.310
we've got the white
background.

02:03:47.310 --> 02:03:50.620
It almost feels like I'm in a
different app, and it loses a

02:03:50.620 --> 02:03:54.630
lot of the fun, the
playfulness of

02:03:54.630 --> 02:03:56.670
the previous screens.

02:03:56.670 --> 02:03:59.500
And you might think, working
on Android design, I might

02:03:59.500 --> 02:04:02.330
cheer for the action bar and
the standard framework

02:04:02.330 --> 02:04:05.160
elements here, but I think,
actually, this is a case where

02:04:05.160 --> 02:04:08.260
sticking with the integrity of
your application, the visual

02:04:08.260 --> 02:04:11.370
integrity of your application,
would be the way to go, to

02:04:11.370 --> 02:04:13.440
have that nice, seamless
throw.

02:04:13.440 --> 02:04:16.590
So I'm a little bit curious
about why you chose to go this

02:04:16.590 --> 02:04:18.650
direction with the screen.

02:04:18.650 --> 02:04:22.180
OREN BENGIGI: Well, the idea was
to have the ability to see

02:04:22.180 --> 02:04:23.800
all the different
faces you took,

